		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Sophism</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">"Sophist" redirects here. For the Dialogue of Plato, see <a href="/wiki/Sophist_(dialogue)" title="Sophist (dialogue)">Sophist (dialogue)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Sophism</b> can mean two very different things: In the modern definition, a sophism is a confusing or illogical argument used for deceiving someone. In Ancient Greece, the <i>sophists</i> were a group of teachers of <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhetoric" title="Rhetoric">rhetoric</a>.</p>
<p>The term <i>sophism</i> originated from <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a> <i>sophistēs</i>, meaning "wise-ist", one who "does" wisdom, one who makes a business out of wisdom (<i>sophós</i> means "wise man").</p>
